## ❌ WRONG: Inconsistent Error Handling

**MUST NOT use this pattern (creates inconsistency):**

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Mixing error display methods
catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof ApiError) {
    setError(err.message); // ❌ Red text - inconsistent with other forms
    // Missing ConfirmDialog
  }
}

// In component:
{error && <div className="p-6 text-center text-red-600">{error}</div>} // ❌ Red text above form
<ConfirmDialog ... /> // May also be present but unused for API errors
```

**Why this is wrong:**

1. ❌ **Inconsistent UX**: Other forms use ConfirmDialog, this form uses red text
2. ❌ **Less visible**: Red text above form is less noticeable than modal dialog
3. ❌ **Confusing**: Users expect consistent error display across all forms
4. ❌ **Maintenance issues**: Different patterns make code harder to maintain

---

## 🎯 Error Type Selection

**MUST use correct ConfirmDialog type for each scenario:**

| Scenario | Type | Example |
| -------- | ---- | ------- |
| **API Communication Error** | `"danger"` | Network error, server error, API error |
| **API Response Failure** | `"danger"` | `result !== "00"` (server returned failure) |
| **Validation Error (Client-side)** | N/A | Display as inline red text next to fields |
| **Success Message** | `"success"` | `result === "00"` (operation succeeded) |
| **Warning Message** | `"warning"` | Duplicate ID, non-critical issues |

**MUST NOT:**

- ❌ Use `type="error"` (this type does not exist, use `"danger"` instead)
- ❌ Use `type="danger"` for success messages (use `"success"`)
- ❌ Use `type="success"` for API errors (use `"danger"`)

